title: Gift Card
description: Shopping for someone else but not sure what to give them? Give them the gift of choice with a Little Big Coffee Roasters gift card. Gift cards are delivered by email and contain instructions to redeem them at checkout. Our gift cards have no additional processing fees.

title: Cafec Abaca Coffee Filter
description: Cafec Abaca coffee filters are made from a mix of wood pulp and manilla hemp. Abaca or Manila Hemp is a more sustainable source compared to wood. We've cupped the coffees made from using these filter, and found an increase in clarity and body. We've made the switch and use these filters exclusively at the shop. Currently we only stock the white cone shaped 4 cup filter paper.

title:
Ipanema Premier Cru Colina 
D'Oro B68 Apricot Black , Brazil, Espresso
description: Brazil REGION: Sul De Minas FARM : Rio Verde VARIETAL: 100% Yellow Bourbon PROCESSING: Natural ALTITUDE: 1018 - 1070 masl PRODUCER: Ipanema Agricola CROP YEAR: 2023 In 2018, Ipanema started their 'Premier Cru' range ; a selection of of very small batch coffee from lots on the highest altitudes of the Estate's oldest farm, Rio Verde. This Coffee is medium-low on acidity has high sweetness has a thick creamy velvety body, cupping notes include red currants, black tea, caramel and sweet nougat finish.

title: GARDELLI SPECIALTY COFFEES (ITALY)
description: MESSAGE FROM THE PEDDLER: Gardelli Specialty Coffees is a roaster that I have always wanted to try. Not only is he an award winning roaster but his ‘single profile’ approach towards roasting (aka omni roast) is always something of interest to us. I have always thought of the single profile approach as a compromise. Simply put, an espresso roast will make for a less complex filter coffee and similarly, a filter roast will make for a less balanced espresso. So if you have a single roast profile for both, logically you can't have the best of both worlds. But superb quality coffee tends to defy logic and these coffees from Gardelli are amazing both ways, albeit better in one way (IMO). Look thru the different coffees and read about them (scan the QR code). You'll be able to tell how much effort had been put into sourcing these coffees and that is half the hard work done. Hope you'll enjoy them as much as we do.

title: Rwanda, Mahembe, Espresso
description: Mahembe Coffee - A Story of Family Legacy and Quality Founded by Justin Musabyimana in 2010 and now managed alongside his son Willy, Mahembe Coffee has grown from a single wet mill on the family plantation to a thriving operation supporting over 600 smallholder farmers in Rwanda's Western Province. Coffee Details: • Region: Nyamasheke District, Western Province • Processing Stations: Two stations across three farms • Varietal: Red Bourbon • Processing: Natural • Altitude: 1800-2000 masl • Crop Year: 2024 • Tasting Notes: Passionfruit, red currants, brown sugar Community Partnership: Mahembe Coffee works directly with over 600 smallholder farmers, maintaining rigorous quality standards by accepting only fully ripe cherries. Their largest farm, Gituntu, spans 14 hectares with 45,000 coffee trees, demonstrating their commitment to both quality and scale. title: Ethiopia, Gelcha Kindu, Filter
description: Ethiopia REGION: Gedeb, Yirgacheffe FARM : Various Smallholder Farms VARIETAL: 74110 PROCESSING: Natural ALTITUDE: 2049 masl WASHING STATION : Gargari Manay Coffee Supplier PLC CROP YEAR: 2025 A good clean natural that is not heavy on process driven flavours, We taste Prunes, slight florals has a black tea like body, brown sugar sweetness Ethiopia – Yirgacheffe Gelcha Kindu G1 Natural Coffee This coffee originates from Galcha Kebele in Gedeb Wereda, within the Gedeo Zone of the renowned Yirgacheffe region in Southern Ethiopia. Grown at 2,049 meters by around 450 smallholder farmers, each with less than 1 hectare, it is a natural-processed coffee of the 74110 varietal. The Gargari Manay Coffee Supplier PLC operates the washing station, with sourcing support from Primrose, their export partner. Farms use organic, traditional methods (though uncertified due to cost), intercropping with local food crops like enset, avocados, and papaya. Environmental challenges include climate change, pest

title: Dripbag Boxset
description: 5 different coffees, 2 bags each. A great way to experience what specialty coffee has to offer.

title: Honduras, Agua Virgen, Espresso
description: Varieties: IHCAFE90 , Catuaí, Lempira Processing: Fully Washed Extended fermentation Altitude: 1628 meters above sea level Tasting notes :Red apples, honey, Dates Jerónimo started his coffee farm, Agua Virgen, in 2012 with just 0.18 hectares despite facing environmental challenges. Over the years, he has expanded his farm to more than five times its original size and refined his cultivation methods. He uses agroforestry systems that help slow cherry maturation, which allows the coffee beans to develop more complex flavors and depth.

title: Kenya, Ndiani, Filter
description: Origin Details: Factory: Ndiaini Factory (part of Rumukia Farmers' Cooperative Society) Location: Mukurweini town, Nyeri County, Kenya Altitude: 1,850 meters above sea level Varietals: SL 28, SL 34, Ruiru 11, Batian Tasting notes: Elderflower, Apricot, Red Currants Production: Producers: ~500 smallholder farmers (280 men, 220 women) Farm Size: Less than 1 hectare per farm Processing: Fully washed method with 24-hour fermentation Drying: 14-21 days on raised beds until 10-12% moisture Processing Method: Cherries are pulped by machine, fermented in cement tanks for 24 hours to break down mucilage, washed with clean water, then sun-dried on raised beds. Growing Conditions: The high altitude and bright red, nutrient-rich soils create ideal conditions for slow cherry maturation. Farmers also grow tea, maize, wheat, potatoes, and kale while raising dairy cattle and chickens. Sustainability: The cooperative focuses on tree planting, irrigation projects, climate change mitigation, and waste ma
